So this is a story that is not a story.
And a story so ancient that it is now fixed: I heard for the first time the bobard saying that "independence means passport control" over 40 years ago.
Yet we have forgotten one interesting point in this interpretation of an old dusty tale.
Why should an independent Scotland follow the instructions of Europe, in fact?
Why exchange London's play against that of Brussels, especially now?
Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely at a dead end.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe has officially died.
Through Europe, parties that oppose the EU or militate for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Euroceptic Alternative Party for Germany, founded only this year and arrived nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the federal elections in September and released the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been a national opposition to the proposed creation of a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the carcan heavy on national economies through accession to the single currency, has led many people to believe that the European Project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments which are experiencing excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Rather, the European system has made it difficult for its members to maintain the exchange rates favourable to German exporters – which German politicians want to maintain.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, the countries of South Europe face an intrinsic problem of productivity vis-à-vis Germany.
The only remedy is to make dark cuts in public wages and expenditure – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current budgetary and monetary problems, there is a greater concern about productivity in Europe.
Following the "green" energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a cost-recognition drawback, as we have seen in Grangemouth.
All wage gels in the world will not prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap US shale gas.
As a result, the growing revolt, particularly in France, is one of the main factors in the EU.
After the war, the French political elite considered the EU as a means of controlling Germany and putting Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport for its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy in a bad way.
Result: the extreme right-wing party of Marine Le Pen, the National Anti-European Front, has just won a crucial partial election, bringing the socialists back to power in third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24% of the votes – an opportune warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot start from the principle that a split of the right will automatically favour the left.
What does Marine Le Pen do with its new popularity with the French white working class?
It wants to use next year's European elections to create a single anti-European anti-money bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-European parties are a good figure in these elections, which is very possible, such a bloc could control the European Parliament for the first time.
That is what I think: very soon, the anti-European and anti-money sentiment unique in Europe will unite and eventually kill the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will return to something that will look more like "the Europe of the Nations (Sovereigners)" free privileged by General de Gaulle.
Germany and some of its satellite economies could retain the euro, but France and South Europe will regain their own currency.
I expect the United Kingdom to take its distance from this project, and I hope it will look soft in the United States.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain will be left to account in the Atlantic.
What about Scotland in all this?
We can decide to be a region of small England (essentially).
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which includes sending for a walk in Berlin and Brussels.
I believe that Scotland could accommodate a more free European agreement provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other countries with similar views would be easier in a non-federal UN Europe.
Otherwise, we should imitate Norway and maintain our economic independence.
The SNP government of Scotland is – and it is to be noted – the anti-austerity political movement that has best succeeded in Europe, as it won a spectacular majority in 2011 based on its opposition to the dark cuts proposed (and implemented) by the Chancellor of the Labour Equiquier, Alistair Darling, and the Conservative/Liberal-Democrat coalition that followed.
