And the heavier devices like laptops will always have to be lined up because they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory authority for mobile phones belongs to the Federal Communications Commission and not to the FAA.
FAA can lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transport safety expert on CBS News, said that mobile phones were always considered to be at risk.
"Mobile phones are a real problem, not only because they could potentially create interference with navigation instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile telephone antennas if they are used on board," Rosenker said.
An industrial advisory committee established by the FAA to address the problem recommended last month that the government allow for a wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on its use.
Detractors such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these prohibitions.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to apply as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one third of passengers forget to turn off their devices, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began to limit the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers were transporting FM radios, the high-tech gadget at that time.
New line aeroplanes depend much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic interference and approved by the FAA.
Airlines have allowed their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruise altitudes for several years.
Airplanes modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more responsive to interference.
The vast majority of line aeroplanes should allow for wider use of electronic devices under the new directives, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit radio transmissions of power much lower than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, only issue minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is one of those that pressurize restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company's leaders commissioned a Kindle electronic book reader line aircraft and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there was none.
This inspired the members of the FAA Advisory Committee with mixed feelings about whether or not the use of devices presents a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers stated that he thought interference from the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee stated that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that the aircraft may interfere with the systems of an aircraft, and that most of them are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to request passengers to turn off their devices during instrument landings under low visibility conditions.
