How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Do you finish typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by the biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho, even estimates that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person making transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet .
The organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this commitment to biometrics, but worry about it.
In 2011 and in France alone, the National Commission on Computer Science and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, hand-shaped or venous network of hands in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified anywhere and anytime," says Justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy in the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology), Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will build on new technologies that will enable new services to be made available to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and venous networks of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work on concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the field of identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the hand contour assume a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - it is not possible to capture these data themselves - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and it takes time.
As a result, research has been carried out for some twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the coloured part of the eye).
Thanks to increased sensor accuracy and the computing capacity of computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The precision of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the past five years, Cyrille Bataller, Director of Accenture R&D Laboratories in Europe, calculates.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible marking, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the present state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vultiet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and within one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognize one person among others) and authentication (make sure the person is the one that he claims to be).
The identification so far concerned the issue of identity papers: we must compare the biometric elements (prints, photos, iris) with the information that the state has on all citizens already filled.
This makes it possible to ensure that one person does not try to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We take back the surveillance camera images and compare them to the photos of celebrities who are freely circulating on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, who is responsible for the commercial development of biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other use: take a quidam photo that does tail in a store, track its progression through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
The authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the partner that points to another", justifies Cyrille Bataller, from Accenture.
But more and more authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by entering his card and placing his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the strike of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and stores of the large distribution: when paying in store with its bank card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader scanning the veins.
Experimentation is planned for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracking to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometric seductive in the eyes of the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer remains in caisse for thirty seconds less, it is significant," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And, finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure housing, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
But, in the absence of extensive studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
The privacy experts, they, continue to worry.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa make me afraid of the worst: widespread surveillance," says Andrew Patrick of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
