Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies have shown that happy dogs are more likely to move their tails to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs are more likely to move them to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trente, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that as in man, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for movement to the left and vice versa, and that both hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordered tail movements of other dogs, researchers have followed animals watching movies where other dogs were.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't be long before we understand why their tails sometimes go on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs films where other dogs were – either a naturalistic version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going more to the left or to the right."
When the animals saw an unexpressed dog move the tail to the right (from the dog's point of view, which removes the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they found a tail turning mainly to the left (again from the dog's point of view that stirs the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think the dogs deliberately communicated with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks that dogs know by experience the movements they should or shouldn't worry about.
He added: "If you encounter several other dogs on several occasions and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tails to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said it was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the dog species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs were turning their heads to the left when they were looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a joyful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by Victoria University in Canada, he said, "Dogs went more easily to a robot dog when their tail moved to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the films or the robots dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it probably won't take long before we understand why their tail moves sometimes on one side and sometimes on the other.
