A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York identified a new species of bald dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for scientific mission to the Observatory for Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Milieus (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identification of new species.
Are you surprised by the discovery of this new species of douphin?
It's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
Although in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge of species classification sciences.
Moreover, it is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to call into question the classification or membership of a species to a genus, family, or even order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences among species.
Today, some of these classifications are called into question because of the progress of genetics.
In the same way, two species very near morphologically were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this sub-family: Pacific-backed dolphins and Atlantic-backed whales.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this a discovery of importance as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had long been known by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, only present here.
Therefore, if a massive mortality problem caused by a viral epidemic or by accidental capture occurs in the region, we may have to deal with the extinction of a species, rather than local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered to be threatened or endangered on the basis of the number of individuals existing on Earth, that is, the stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from its neighbouring stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new species was discovered, its stock automatically became smaller, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, the more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It must be known that the marine environment is the least well known.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, than to know what lives in the Marianne pit, only 11 kilometres from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent in the search for life on other planets than in marine research, and it's a long time since it changes.
